fields.question: Birth registration: at least 75% of births registered
Death registration: at least 60% of deaths registered
Maternal death reviews: at least 90% of maternal deaths notified and reviewed
Maternal death is a notifiable event
Policy and mechanisms are in place to review all maternal deaths
National panel to review maternal deaths in place
National panel to review maternal deaths in place and meeting regularly
Maternal deaths are captured by the national health information system
Coverage of registration: cause of death > 60%
Quality of care assessment conducted (SPA, EMOC)
CRVS improvement plan approved by country government in place
CRVS assessment conducted
Health indicators additional information
Overall- 8 indicators from 2010 - 2012
Met need for contraception
Antenatal care coverage (ANC 4)
Antiretroviral prophylaxis for PMTCT
Skilled attendant at birth
Postnatal care for mothers and babies
Exclusive breastfeeding for six months
DTP-3
Antibiotic treatment for pneumonia
Data for the 3 impact indicators are available based on data collected in the preceding 3 years
National eHealth strategy and plan is in place
Policy implemented
All districts are part of a national web based system to report health data and receive feedback
Total health expenditure per capita was tracked during the two preceding years, by financing source
A NHA was conducted/planned in the last/next 2-3 years
RMNCH expenditure per capita is tracked during the two preceding years, by financing source
A country-led reporting system is in place for externally funded expenditure and predictable commitments These include "compacts" or other similar mechanisms
Reviews of health spending from all financial sources, including spending on RMNCH, are conducted annually as part of broader health sector reviews
The country has conducted a annual health sector review in the last year
A health sector performance report for the preceding year is available in the public domain
